But yeah. I figured out my own deal that worked for me and it continues to work. I haven’t missed drinking in a very long time. I honestly don’t even think about it much anymore; it’s just something I don’t do, like I don’t eat celery because I think it’s gross. ¯\_(ツ)_/¯

(Sidebar: “In The Realm Of Hungry Ghosts” is a phenomenal read and radically informed how I believe a lot of “ills” in are society are genuinely related to overall lack of community care, especially among our most vulnerable populations, but that’s a WHOLE other thing).

What ultimately ended up working for me was treating it like any other problem & seeking to understand as much as I could, from a scientific & psychological standpoint. These books helped me so much in knowing what I was actually dealing with. https://t.co/5lXRnTh4wv

And even in the online sobriety world, it was VERY overwhelming cis-heteronormative. And overall, there is a LOT of messaging that there is One Way to be sober and if you’re not doing that, you’re doing it wrong. Which… did not jive for me. At all.

- more conservative makeup of the groups available to me weren’t my jam. Ex: I genuinely don’t know how I could have had a sponsor, because straights were supposed to be same-gender paired, & gays with opposite, to prevent possible romantic issues. Idk where that left my bi ass.

It’s wild to me to look at how my recovery has changed over the last 6 years. I struggled early on finding space in the sober community, online or off, that felt right for me. A 12-step program was helpful for me very early on, but both the material itself and the -

Almost a decade after that relationship ended, I realized that it had A LOT of shades of emotional abuse; my inarticulate fury and refusal to let go was my defense against the constant gaslighting I got from my ex & others, because oh it wasn’t that bad.

In my early 20s, I was once talking about a bad past relationship with someone, they kept pushing me on why I couldn’t forgive the dude & get over it, and I just couldn’t articulate why I couldn’t, I was frustrated to the point of tears, and that was kind of that.
Throughout my life, I’ve been told I should forgive people who’ve wronged me, even when they’ve made no attempt to make amends, for “my own benefit”, and to that, I say “get fucked”. 😌

LRT - “Refusing to forgive acknowledges just how deep your hurt really is: When the people around you want you to just move on or let it go, your fury honors what really happened. Sometimes that feeling is the only ‘proof’ we have.”

And (sort of MM spoilers I guess?) I very much appreciated that Riley’s journey didn’t involve a relapse. Yes, they are INCREDIBLY common in the real world, but it’s just nice to see a sober character whose whole major plot point isn’t relapsing.

Luke’s story in Hill House was one of my favorite things about that whole show, as was Riley’s in Midnight Mass. Both just do such a great job of showing the struggle & heartbreak, the ripple effects, the moments of triumph, without condemning the characters experiencing them.

As someone who’s five+ years sober from booze myself, it is SO apparent when an addiction narrative is being crafted by someone with no idea of what they’re talking about, and vice versa. I honestly struggle to think of much (mainstream) media that’s gotten it right.

Finding out Mike Flanagan has dealt with addiction and is three years sober honestly gives me a new appreciation for much of his work, and now I absolutely understand why those depictions of addiction have been some of my favorites in recent media.
